	(lib_symbols)
	(text_box "PCB LAYOUT AND ROUTING\nThe design includes a 4 layer board with the following stackup: Signal, Ground, Signal + Power, ground\nThis ensures all the traces have proper reference plane, L1 reference L2 and L3 reference L4.\nAll the grounds and 3.3V power are uncut planes thus ensure proper SI and reduces EMI from cuts.\n\nRS485 standard dictates A and B are differential pairs and should routed with 120 ohms differential impendance and ethernet standard dictates the differential pairs should be routed with 100 ohms differential impendance.\nBoth standards have been followed by using kicad's inbuilt calculator to get the required width and separation gap.\nMeadering has been used to achieved precise length matching on the different differential pairs as stipulated by the standard\n\nThe pcb layout has followed the recommended layout provided by the different datasheets.\nTracks have enough separation to minimize crosstalk and improve signal integrity\nThermal reliefs are used on the different copper pours.\n\nSoftaware test\nA python script will be used to test the different interfaces.\nThe program will ping the ethernent and check if host is up, hence verifying the ethernet\nSend a \"hello world\" over uart to a pc connected via a uart to ttl converter hence verify uart\nfor i2c, a simple loop that loops all the 7 bit address space and returns the address of  the device connected should work.\nfor spi, a sensor sending data over spi can be used to verify spi is cable of receiving data and also send data over to the sensor.\n\nSignal ringing on high speed lines might be an ensure but probing with an oscilloscope can be used to check \n"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 155.702 13.97 0)
